State Transport Minister Sidda Raghava Rao on Friday reiterated the governmentâ€™s resolve to realise zero road mishap through sustained campaign to bring awareness among people on road safety norms.It was the collective responsibility of every individual to follow traffic rules such as wearing helmets while driving two-wheelers, fastening seat belts while driving car and eschew liquor while behind the wheels, he said after releasing a poster on safe driving brought out by the Road Transport Authority, marking the Road Safety Week campaign that will continue till January 28.A Dynamic Driving school would be set up by the Centre at Darsi in Prakasam district at a cost of Rs. 25 crore to provide advanced training to drivers, he added.Sporting a helmet, TDP national vice-President Magunta Srinivasulu Reddy took part in a motorcycle rally to impress upon the people on the helmet rule. Regional Transport Officer K.Ramprasad said 212 persons had died in 205 accidents involving two-wheelers in the district last year. Head injuries accounted to 201 deaths.Chittoor Staff Reporter adds: Deputy Transport Commissioner (Chittoor) Ch. Pratap on Friday inaugurated the Road Safety Week at DTC grounds here. Addressing the departmental staff, the official said that on an average about 7,000 accident-related deaths were happening in the State, while the number of injured was crossing over 30,000.